  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Inscription for the Xingfu Monastery in the Southern City of Dadu
  author: Lee Je-hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The law of karma in Buddhism teaches that cultivating virtue brings fitting reward, just as watering the roots allows us to harvest fruit. Its power guides the lost multitude toward merit and grace. South of the southern city of the capital stands a temple called Xingfu. Though not distant from the markets, it possesses a tranquil, mountain-valley charm where patrons gather daily, allowing the monks to sustain themselves and pursue the Way.

    Once, a Korean monk named Wondam purchased five acres of land and, together with his fellow disciples Sungahn and Fayun, laid the foundation and raised a hall. There was also the Lady Rim of Changseong County, also Korean. Since the time of the World Ancestor Emperor, she had found favor at the imperial palace, receiving lavish rewards. Ever seeking a way to bless the throne in gratitude, she heard of this great undertaking and joyfully contributed many thousands in paper currency to sustain the construction, and granted fifty acres of fertile land to supply the daily offerings. The craftsmen were assembled, materials gathered. The upper beams were set and the lower eaves completed, beginning in autumn of the second year of Huangqing and finishing in spring of the fourth year of Yanyou. The ridgepoles rise high, the chambers and windows shine clean; the practice hall gleams bright, and the Buddha images stand in solemn majesty. Truly, when there are those to guide, the work reaches perfection.

    They bound future generations: let Korean monks forever preside over the teaching seats, for their mastery of the precepts is unmatched. Wondam, Sungahn, Fayun, and Lady Rim—thousands of miles from their homeland, they gathered without summons to accomplish this noble deed. With modest effort, they achieved complete success. Is this not the flowering of karmic seeds from ages past? From this time forth, above they shall invoke blessings upon the court, and below rain grace upon all sentient beings. Though heaven's palace has long witnessed the rope of wisdom, and the great wind has never extinguished a poor woman's lamp, who can deny that karma bears fruit? I, being Korean myself and companion to Wondam and his brothers, cannot refuse to set their words to writing, that future generations might hear.
  footnotes:
    - Xingfu Monastery was a significant Buddhist institution built in the Yuan capital (modern-day Beijing) by Korean monks and patrons during the early 14th century.
    - The reference to 'Sakyamuni's rope' and 'the poor woman's lamp' are classical Buddhist parables illustrating the manifestation of karmic reward across lives and circumstances.
    - Lee Je-hyeon (1287-1367) was a distinguished Korean Confucian scholar and official who served in the Yuan court, making him ideally positioned to compose this inscription honoring both Buddhist and Korean interests.
